{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513159"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:05:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:05:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12027"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12027"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.38,0.15,0.13,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4605"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59337"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4605"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12027"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44748"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"1742"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6953"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6977"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18401"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59337"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man is admitted to the intensive care unit (ICU) with severe lethargy and shortness of breath with increasing oxygen requirements. He has a medical history of ischaemic heart disease, stage 4 chronic kidney disease and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His medications include metformin and gliclazide. Soon after admission to the ICU, he is sedated, intubated and ventilated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe subsequent arterial blood gas analysis shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.08 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3 8 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2 20 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Elactate 18 mmol/L (0-2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eglucose 9.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management intervention for the blood gas picture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV sodium bicarbonate","Haemodialysis","IV insulin infusion","IV 0.9% NaCl bolus","Hyperventilation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in the stem is suffering from lactic acidosis with pre-existing impaired renal function. Metformin is a biguanide oral hypoglycaemic agent which can cause type B lactic acidosis by increasing lactic acid production whilst impairing its removal by the kidneys and liver. Metformin is contraindicated in the presence of severe hepatic or renal impairment and if resultant lactic acidosis develops, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E or continuous haemofiltration is required to remove the metformin and correct the acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment of acidosis with \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E alone often fails to correct acidosis and may cause intracellular acidosis and hypernatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV insulin infusion\u003C/strong\u003E alone is unlikely to correct the acidosis by itself as it would not remove the metformin and address the resultant lactic acidosis. Whilst insulin therapy may be indicated in some situations such as diabetic ketoacidosis or hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state (HHS), the blood gas results and clinical scenario are not consistent with this. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EIV 0.9% NaCl bolus\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated if the patient is haemodynamically unstable but will not remove the metformin from circulation or manage the lactic acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperventilation\u003C/strong\u003E is the body\u0027s natural response to metabolic acidosis in order to increase the pH of the blood. However, hypocapnia may adversely affect arterial blood oxygenation, especially in the presence of lung disease. Once again, hyperventilation will be insufficient in excreting the metformin and subsequent lactic acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metformin is contraindicated in the presence of severe hepatic or renal impairment as it can induce lactic acidosis."],"references":["DeFronzo R, Fleming GA, Chen K, Bicsak TA. Metformin-associated lactic acidosis: Current perspectives on causes and risk. Metabolism. 2016;65(2):20-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26773926/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44748"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12027"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44748"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-07T10:02:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-07T10:03:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4605"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59337"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount"